  "answer": "**This specific passage and imagery—praising a Hindu sannyasi as \"the Abraham of Love\" who shatters \"the idol of the Self,\" fused with the shahada (\"La ilaha illa Allah\") via a \"river of 'La'\" hiding the \"pearl of 'illa-Allah'\"—do not appear in the Falsafa corpus.**\n\nMultiple searches for key phrases (\"river of 'La' pearl 'illa-Allah'\", \"pearl of illa-Allah\", \"Abraham of Love\", \"idol of the Self\", \"la ilaha\", and variants like \"pearl river Allah\", \"no god pearl\"), the term \"sannyasi\" (and \"sannyasin\"), and related concepts yielded zero results. Queries for poetry, Sufi works, or authors like Rumi also returned no matches.[^1]\n\nThe corpus focuses on 38 translated philosophical and classical texts; while it includes diverse thinkers, it lacks this particular syncretic Muslim poetry praising a Hindu ascetic (possibly evoking figures like Kabir, Bulleh Shah, or Bedil, but none are represented here).\n\n[^1]: Searches conducted across English translations; no relevant works, chapters, or paragraphs found. Corpus metadata confirmed via `list_works` (e.g., no poetry/Sufi genre hits).",
